VIX Futures Climb, VStoxx Rises to 12-Week High on Greek Crisis

-- B y   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-06-16T12:47:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-16/vix-futures-climb-vstoxx-rises-to-12-week-high-on-greek-crisis.html
Futures on the benchmark index for
U.S. stock options rose and  Europe ’s  VStoxx Index (V2X)  climbed to the
highest since March increased as equities tumbled around the
world on concern that Europe’s debt crisis is worsening.  July futures on the VIX, as the Chicago Board Options
Exchange Volatility Index of Standard & Poor’s 500 Index options
is known, gained 2.5 percent to 21.45 at 8:30 a.m. in  New York .
The VStoxx, which measures the cost of protecting against a
decline in the Euro Stoxx 50 Index, rose 12 percent to 25.87 in
Frankfurt. The Euro Stoxx 50 stock index fell 1.3 percent.  The MSCI All-Country World Index slid 1.2 percent to a
three-month low, the euro slumped and European government
default risk climbed to a record as Greek Prime Minister  George Papandreou  battled to keep his job and pass austerity measures.  “It’s something that’s becoming increasingly alarming from
our perspective,” Dean Curnutt, president of New York-based
Macro Risk Advisors LLC, which advises institutions on
derivatives, said in an interview with Erik Schatzker on
Bloomberg Television’s “Inside Track.” “Everyone’s looking at
 Greece .”  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jeff Kearns in New York at 
 jkearns3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 